# SSH, Package Management, Scheduling & systemd

Lab 1 â€“ SSH Key Setup
ðŸŽ¯ Objective

Setup SSH key-based authentication and disable password login.

Step 1: Generate SSH Key

Run the following command on your local machine:

ssh-keygen

Press Enter to accept default location.

Key will be generated inside:

~/.ssh/id_rsa
~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub
Step 2: Copy Public Key to Remote Server
ssh-copy-id username@remote_server_ip

Example:

ssh-copy-id ubuntu@192.168.1.10
Step 3: Disable Password Login

Open SSH configuration file on remote server:

sudo nano /etc/ssh/sshd_config

Find and change:

PasswordAuthentication no

Restart SSH service:

sudo systemctl restart sshd
Step 4: Test Login

Now try login:

ssh username@remote_server_ip

You should login without password.

â° Lab 2 â€“ Cron Job
ðŸŽ¯ Objective

Run a command every 5 minutes using cron.

Step 1: Edit Crontab
crontab -e
Step 2: Add Below Line
*/5 * * * * echo "Test" >> /tmp/test.log1
Step 3: Verify Cron Job

Wait 5 minutes and check:

cat /tmp/test.log1

You should see:

Test
Test
âš™ï¸ Lab 3 â€“ systemd Timer
ðŸŽ¯ Objective

Create a systemd timer to run a script automatically.

Step 1: Create Script
sudo nano /usr/local/bin/systemd_script.sh

Add:

#!/bin/bash
echo "Hello Systemd" >> /tmp/systemd.log1

Make it executable:

sudo chmod +x /usr/local/bin/systemd_script.sh
Step 2: Create Service File
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/systemd-test.service

Add:

[Unit]
Description=Simple Systemd Test Service

[Service]
ExecStart=/usr/local/bin/systemd_script.sh
Step 3: Create Timer File
sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/systemd-test.timer

Add:

[Unit]
Description=Run Systemd Test Every 5 Minutes

[Timer]
OnBootSec=1min
OnUnitActiveSec=5min
Unit=systemd-test.service

[Install]
WantedBy=timers.target
Step 4: Enable and Start Timer

Reload systemd:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload

Enable timer:

sudo systemctl enable systemd-test.timer

Start timer:

sudo systemctl start systemd-test.timer
Step 5: Verify Timer

Check timer status:

systemctl list-timers

Check log output:

cat /tmp/systemd.log1
